124
00:07:09.840 --> 00:07:13.640
So this creates a problem when we want to talk about prevalence, right?

125
00:07:13.740 --> 00:07:16.240
Because who has loss of Y if it looks like this?

126
00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:20.930
So you have to define a threshold in this continuum, and, for

127
00:07:20.960 --> 00:07:24.760
example, by using 5% threshold and applying that to UK

128
00:07:24.940 --> 00:07:27.650
Biobank, we see that at study entry,

129
00:07:29.280 --> 00:07:31.120
20% of these individuals

130
00:07:31.940 --> 00:07:35.560
in the UK Biobank had loss of Y in more than 5% of their blood

131
00:07:35.620 --> 00:07:35.940
cells

132
00:07:36.940 --> 00:07:37.940
going into this study.

133
00:07:39.940 --> 00:07:42.800
That's a high number, and you see how it increases with age, right?

134
00:07:43.900 --> 00:07:44.740
It's almost linear.

135
00:07:47.420 --> 00:07:50.140
So if you think about it, in this age span,

136
00:07:51.260 --> 00:07:53.420
there is more than 10 million men in the UK.

137
00:07:54.160 --> 00:07:56.860
And if UK Biobank is representative for the

138
00:07:57.540 --> 00:08:01.480
