00:08:41.880 --> 00:08:44.000
cells. It's a very high number, right?

152
00:08:44.780 --> 00:08:48.280
But it's probably much more than that because

153
00:08:49.120 --> 00:08:50.520
when we look in single-cell data,

154
00:08:51.360 --> 00:08:54.180
we see loss of Y cells in all individuals,

155
00:08:56.380 --> 00:08:57.000
every man.

156
00:08:58.000 --> 00:08:59.860
So we can use

157
00:09:00.800 --> 00:09:04.060
single-cell data to detect loss of Y in single cells.

158
00:09:04.200 --> 00:09:06.020
Different types of single-cell data have been done.

159
00:09:06.500 --> 00:09:07.820
So basically,

