Over the lifespan, they acquire some truncal mutations,

1266
01:11:29.682 --> 01:11:33.562
including at some point, maybe p53, but lots of passenger mutations

1267
01:11:33.662 --> 01:11:37.522
as well. And so these will show up in 100% of the cells

1268
01:11:37.622 --> 01:11:39.762
of the tumor that grows out eventually.

1269
01:11:40.482 --> 01:11:44.442
Now, over time of tumor evolution, once the tumor is established, we

1270
01:11:44.522 --> 01:11:47.062
also acquire a subclonal mutation.

1271
01:11:47.122 --> 01:11:50.572
So there might be a mutation in only 30% of the cells or another

1272
01:11:50.662 --> 01:11:53.022
mutation that we find in 70% of the cells.

1273
01:11:53.452 --> 01:11:57.232
And through genomic sequencing, we can actually resolve these mutations and when

1274
01:11:57.262 --> 01:11:58.892
they occur during tumor evolution.

1275
01:11:59.982 --> 01:12:03.942
So when we did this for p53 mutations and loss of Y in

1276
01:12:03.982 --> 01:12:07.822
the TCGA cancer data set, we could rank them based

1277
01:12:07.862 --> 01:12:11.222
on when they occurred. So in this plot, we have p53

1278
01:12:11.302 --> 01:12:14.942
mutation clonality, or measured as the cancer cell fraction.

1279
01:12:15.002 --> 01:12:17.802
So the number of cancer cells that actually has this variant

1280
01:12:18.702 --> 01:12:22.542
in red. And then we have the cancer cell fraction of loss

1281
01:12:22.582 --> 01:12:26.202
of Y in blue. And you can see on the far left in uveal

1282
01:12:26.222 --> 01:12:29.962
melanoma, that actually p53 mutations are extremely rare.

1283
01:12:30.122 --> 01:12:31.862
And in this data set, we didn't have any.

1284
01:12:32.442 --> 01:12:35.982
Yet loss of Y has really high cancer cell fraction, meaning it's

1285
01:12:36.042 --> 01:12:39.442
clonal in these tumors and it's a truncal and early event.

1286
01:12:39.642 --> 01:12:42.842
So this is probably a driver in this particular disease.

1287
01:12:43.302 --> 01:12:46.942
Now, as you move to the right, you can see that p53 mutations, and of course this

1288
01:12:46.982 --> 01:12:50.902
is known, tend to be clonal, so their cancer cell fraction is very close to

1289
01:12:50.962 --> 01:12:51.102
one.

1290
01:12:52.082 --> 01:12:54.702
These are initiating events, or at least very early events.

1291
01:12:55.291 --> 01:12:59.002
And then the distribution of loss of Y cancer cell fraction tends to be

1292
01:12:59.042 --> 01:13:01.342
broad and also less. So what does this mean?

1293
01:13:01.882 --> 01:13:05.702
This means that as a p53 mutation existed earlier, and then

1294
01:13:05.762 --> 01:13:09.482
we ended up with a spread of loss of Y as the tumor progressively lost

1295
01:13:09.842 --> 01:13:13.342
Y chromosomes in the cells, caused by p53

1296
01:13:13.402 --> 01:13:16.934
absence.And I'm just highlighting the two that I

1297
01:13:17.254 --> 01:13:20.794
talked to you about before, uveal melanoma and then the lung

1298
01:13:20.894 --> 01:13:24.804
squamous carcinoma. Again, early P53 mutations and then

1299
01:13:25.434 --> 01:13:28.394
sort of loss of Y as a spread in a subclonal fashion.

1300
01:13:30.014 --> 01:13:33.664
So what is most important is can loss of Y tell us about

1301
01:13:33.694 --> 01:13:37.614
outcome? You've seen from previous talks that it's just a case for loss of Y in the

1302
01:13:37.694 --> 01:13:41.474
blood and in bladder cancer. And when we looked at this in the TCJ, we

1303
01:13:41.554 --> 01:13:45.234
also found some tumor types where loss of Y is strongly associated with

1304
01:13:45.334 --> 01:13:48.074
outcome. That includes uveal melanoma, where

1305
01:13:48.154 --> 01:13:52.054
patients whose tumors had loss of

1306
01:13:52.174 --> 01:13:56.154
Y really showed a much poorer outcome than those whose tumors

1307
01:13:56.164 --> 01:13:59.934
retained the Y chromosome, prostate cancer, where there's very

1308
01:13:59.974 --> 01:14:02.494
few loss of Y cases actually in primary tumors.

1309
01:14:02.554 --> 01:14:05.634
It increases with metastasis, but in primary tumors it's rare.

1310
01:14:06.214 --> 01:14:06.854
Again, these

1311
01:14:07.734 --> 01:14:11.554
patients had much worse outcome, and the same is true for mesothelioma,

1312
01:14:11.734 --> 01:14:13.514
again, where loss of Y tumors

1313
01:14:14.534 --> 01:14:18.234
tend to predict that the patient will do worse than if their tumors retain their Y

1314
01:14:18.354 --> 01:14:18.814
chromosome.

1315
01:14:20.714 --> 01:14:24.594
So we end up showing, and this is published work, and I'm not going to

1316
01:14:24.614 --> 01:14:28.014
have time to go into this, but we also showed for uveal melanoma that there's an

1317
01:14:28.054 --> 01:14:31.314
association with aggressiveness, rate of

1318
01:14:31.354 --> 01:14:35.014
metastasis, other aggressiveness markers, including EMT,

1319
01:14:35.914 --> 01:14:39.874
and other predictive features in uveal melanoma, and yes,

1320
01:14:39.954 --> 01:14:42.394
I will not have time to go into this as it's published.

1321
01:14:42.454 --> 01:14:43.114
So

1322
01:14:44.274 --> 01:14:47.444
I want to actually spend some time on new and unpublished work today.

1323
01:14:47.994 --> 01:14:51.334
So all of what I've shown you from the TCGA was based on exome

1324
01:14:51.374 --> 01:14:55.334
sequencing. We have recently, in a collaboration with Gaddy Getz at the Broad

1325
01:14:55.374 --> 01:14:58.514
Institute and Intercross, a company based here in San Diego,

1326
01:14:59.554 --> 01:15:03.334
performed analysis of whole genome sequencing from the Cancer Genome Atlas.

1327
01:15:03.394 --> 01:15:06.604
So these are really, really nice high-quality whole genomes,

1328
01:15:07.274 --> 01:15:09.214
with PCR-free whole sequencing.

1329
01:15:10.054 --> 01:15:13.954
And what this allows us to do now is to go beyond the protein coding genes

1330
01:15:14.014 --> 01:15:16.374
on the Y chromosome. What can we do with this?

1331
01:15:16.614 --> 01:15:20.194
We can resolve structural variations, we can start looking at non-coding

1332
01:15:20.254 --> 01:15:24.134
alterations, and we can also get increased coverage of protein coding

1333
01:15:24.174 --> 01:15:28.134
genes. And so in an early discovery here, and that's

1334
01:15:28.154 --> 01:15:32.104
this work done by Luis Corchete Sanchez, who is here, and if you're

1335
01:15:32.114 --> 01:15:34.283
interested in this, please go and check out his poster,

1336
01:15:35.234 --> 01:15:38.934
shows that actually many tumors have structural variants that involve the Y

1337
01:15:39.034 --> 01:15:42.654
chromosome. Over 30% in sarcomas, which might not be

1338
01:15:42.694 --> 01:15:46.494
surprising because they tend to be genopically unstable, but

1339
01:15:46.554 --> 01:15:50.454
also 25% in bladder cancer and high percentage in other

1340
01:15:50.494 --> 01:15:53.914
tumor types have structural variations, interactions, large-scale

1341
01:15:54.274 --> 01:15:56.314
genomic aberrations on the Y chromosome.

1342
01:15:57.594 --> 01:16:01.074
These can be broken down into different types. So there are deletions.

1343
01:16:01.134 --> 01:16:04.594
These deletions are not loss of Y. These are smaller deletions or partial

1344
01:16:04.694 --> 01:16:06.554
deletions of Y chromosome segments.

1345
01:16:07.534 --> 01:16:11.054
We have tandem duplications, inversions, but the largest chunk of

1346
01:16:11.094 --> 01:16:14.734
alterations on the Y chromosome involve interchromosomal

1347
01:16:15.594 --> 01:16:19.434
rearrangements. So that means part of the Y chromosome is attached to some

1348
01:16:19.474 --> 01:16:23.034
other part of the genome, some autosomes, or potentially the X

1349
01:16:23.074 --> 01:16:25.854
chromosome. And I'm just going to show you one example.

1350
01:16:25.894 --> 01:16:27.674
This is from the prostate cancer cohort.

1351
01:16:28.054 --> 01:16:31.934
You can see the Y chromosome on the bottom, and all these lines

1352
01:16:32.014 --> 01:16:35.614
show a structural variation where some part of the Y

1353
01:16:35.654 --> 01:16:39.274
chromosome goes to another part in the genome.

1354
01:16:39.284 --> 01:16:43.074
There's a lot of activity beyond just loss of Y

1355
01:16:43.084 --> 01:16:45.144
that's going on in these cancer genomes.

1356
01:16:46.314 --> 01:16:49.514
What's interesting is when Luis checked whether loss of

1357
01:16:49.614 --> 01:16:53.514
Y co-occurred with some of these structural variations, we

1358
01:16:53.534 --> 01:16:56.794
saw something very interesting, and I want to make a couple of points here in this

1359
01:16:56.814 --> 01:17:00.714
particular graph. So the light blue shows just loss of Y, so the whole

1360
01:17:00.794 --> 01:17:04.714
chromosome is gone. And this is a very important point to make, is

1361
01:17:04.754 --> 01:17:08.634
that the most frequent alteration involving the Y chromosome in

1362
01:17:08.694 --> 01:17:12.534
cancer is its entire loss. And this will have implications for how we

1363
01:17:12.554 --> 01:17:16.354
think about Y chromosome loss because it's not maybe just one gene or

1364
01:17:16.414 --> 01:17:18.574
maybe two genes, or a small region.

1365
01:17:19.054 --> 01:17:22.994
There seems to be some benefit to really getting rid of the whole thing in

1366
01:17:23.054 --> 01:17:26.874
its entirety. However, we did see loss of Y, even complete

1367
01:17:26.934 --> 01:17:30.834
loss of Y with some structural alterations, which are the dark

1368
01:17:30.874 --> 01:17:34.854
blue blocks. And now how can you get this situation, right?

1369
01:17:34.883 --> 01:17:38.534
You lose the Y chromosome. How can you also have a structural variation

1370
01:17:38.554 --> 01:17:42.494
including a Y chromosome? Now, there are multiple explanations

1371
01:17:42.534 --> 01:17:46.374
for this. So, for example, they could occur in the same cells if it's a

1372
01:17:46.434 --> 01:17:50.194
partial loss of the Y chromosome and then some other part, however small,

1373
01:17:50.614 --> 01:17:52.214
is attached to another chromosome.

1374
01:17:53.414 --> 01:17:55.934
They could occur in the same cell after whole genome doublings.

1375
01:17:56.014 --> 01:17:59.564
A lot of tumors double their genomes. That leads to two Y chromosomes.

1376
01:18:00.034 --> 01:18:03.774
One Y chromosome could be lost, and then the other one, or a part of it, could be

1377
01:18:03.874 --> 01:18:06.794
attached to another autosome, potentially.

1378
01:18:06.814 --> 01:18:10.074
And then they could just be different alterations and different tumor subclones.

1379
01:18:10.134 --> 01:18:13.694
I've shown you that loss of Y tends to be subclonal in many tumor types.

1380
01:18:13.763 --> 01:18:17.494
So you can have loss of Y in some part of the tumor, and another clone might

1381
01:18:17.554 --> 01:18:21.194
have a structural variant moving part of the Y chromosome elsewhere.

1382
01:18:22.834 --> 01:18:25.884
And as I mentioned, Luis has a poster. This is the number.

1383
01:18:26.234 --> 01:18:29.754
Please go check it out. He will be presenting on Monday from 9:00 to 12:00.

1384
01:18:30.654 --> 01:18:33.674
So now I'm going to shift gears slightly

1385
01:18:35.154 --> 01:18:39.034
and talk a little bit about a study that we're working on, on loss of Y

1386
01:18:39.094 --> 01:18:42.953
in pediatric tumors. Why is this a really important field?

1387
01:18:43.554 --> 01:18:47.284
You've heard a lot about how loss of Y is associated with aging, how

1388
01:18:47.434 --> 01:18:49.674
as men age, the Y chromosome gets lost.

1389
01:18:50.234 --> 01:18:53.634
In fact, I didn't have time to talk about it, but we also saw some aging

1390
01:18:53.694 --> 01:18:57.534
association for loss of Y

1391
01:18:57.544 --> 01:18:58.194
in tumors.

1392
01:18:59.114 --> 01:19:03.094
Now, we wanted to know if we see loss of Y in pediatric

1393
01:19:03.174 --> 01:19:06.094
tumors where we have no influence of aging long-term

1394
01:19:06.454 --> 01:19:10.074
effects or exposures to smoking over a long time,

1395
01:19:10.414 --> 01:19:13.604
if we could still see Y chromosome loss, and it would tell us whether it's a

1396
01:19:13.614 --> 01:19:13.944
driver.

1397
01:19:14.834 --> 01:19:16.594
So this is work done by Pracheeta Dave,

1398
01:19:17.414 --> 01:19:21.114
Andre Leschziner, and Teo Rivera-Vilhs, who is also here and also has a

1399
01:19:21.154 --> 01:19:25.068
poster that I encourage you to check out.So we took the Open

1400
01:19:25.158 --> 01:19:29.088
PedCan cohort, which is already pre-processed, and looked at their copy number

1401
01:19:29.138 --> 01:19:30.838
and checked for Y chromosome losses.

1402
01:19:31.198 --> 01:19:34.998
You can see here ranked in blocks by the number of tumors in each tumor

1403
01:19:35.038 --> 01:19:39.028
type and in the copy number heat map, you can see the dark blue indicates

1404
01:19:39.078 --> 01:19:42.917
loss of Y. So what's interesting and actually concordant with adult tumors is

1405
01:19:42.998 --> 01:19:45.618
that gliomas tend to hold onto their Y chromosomes.

1406
01:19:45.638 --> 01:19:47.908
They very rarely lose Y chromosomes.

1407
01:19:48.318 --> 01:19:52.078
However, second, we found that neuroblastoma is a tumor

1408
01:19:52.178 --> 01:19:54.958
type that has very frequent Y chromosome loss.

1409
01:19:55.937 --> 01:19:59.858
And you can see there's other tumor types, including medulloblastoma and some on

1410
01:19:59.898 --> 01:20:03.138
the right that are less resolved, but there are some tumor types in

1411
01:20:03.178 --> 01:20:07.048
children that really have Y chromosome loss we cannot explain with

1412
01:20:07.118 --> 01:20:08.998
aging or smoking exposure.

1413
01:20:09.958 --> 01:20:13.458
So overall, in this cohort, about 18% of the tumors had Y

1414
01:20:13.538 --> 01:20:17.418
chromosome loss. That compares to about 30% to 40% among adult

1415
01:20:17.478 --> 01:20:21.238
tumors, and as I said, it cannot be explained by sort of

1416
01:20:21.338 --> 01:20:22.618
age or other

1417
01:20:23.738 --> 01:20:26.818
environmental exposures, so potentially in

1418
01:20:26.858 --> 01:20:29.298
these diseases, it would be a driver.

1419
01:20:30.718 --> 01:20:34.318
So this is just to quantify. We saw a loss of Y in about 25% of

1420
01:20:34.328 --> 01:20:37.678
neuroblastoma, so it's a really frequent alteration.

1421
01:20:37.778 --> 01:20:41.418
And what was interesting is that it's associated with higher tumor stage.

1422
01:20:41.458 --> 01:20:45.358
So most of the loss of Y tumors are stage four, which is the worst stage.

1423
01:20:46.358 --> 01:20:49.678
And, if you know anything about neuroblastoma,

1424
01:20:49.818 --> 01:20:53.398
MYCN focal amplification is one of the most

1425
01:20:53.438 --> 01:20:57.118
frequent events that's also a poor prognosis predictor.

1426
01:20:57.158 --> 01:21:01.138
And we found that MYCN amplification actually tends to be mutually exclusive

1427
01:21:01.178 --> 01:21:03.338
with loss of Y. So what does this mean?

1428
01:21:03.518 --> 01:21:07.298
Loss of Y is associated with stage four and poor outcome,

1429
01:21:07.778 --> 01:21:09.798
but it's not overlapping with MYCN.

1430
01:21:10.058 --> 01:21:13.818
So there seem to be two different mechanisms potentially arriving at the

1431
01:21:13.878 --> 01:21:17.578
same biology. We don't know at this point, but just sort

1432
01:21:17.618 --> 01:21:21.458
of putting another high-risk factor with loss of Y

1433
01:21:21.518 --> 01:21:23.638
on the map in a pediatric cancer type.

1434
01:21:24.078 --> 01:21:25.978
So if you're interested in learning more about this,

1435
01:21:27.158 --> 01:21:29.378
please go and see Teo's poster.

1436
01:21:30.638 --> 01:21:31.978
All right. There he goes.

1437
01:21:33.577 --> 01:21:37.338
Okay. So finally, I want to end up with just a little bit of

1438
01:21:37.358 --> 01:21:38.858
relevance, therapeutic relevance.

1439
01:21:38.958 --> 01:21:42.758
In the end, we want to cure cancer, and loss of Y may actually

1440
01:21:42.798 --> 01:21:46.198
present a specific vulnerability of how we can do that.

1441
01:21:46.918 --> 01:21:49.918
And to give you some early data here, we used

1442
01:21:50.718 --> 01:21:53.958
data from the DepMap from the Broad Institute, which is actually an

1443
01:21:54.018 --> 01:21:57.958
experiment knocking out genes across 1,000 cell lines, so

1444
01:21:57.998 --> 01:21:58.598
genome-wide

1445
01:21:59.478 --> 01:22:03.178
knockout of all the genes. And what were we looking for?

1446
01:22:03.638 --> 01:22:07.418
So we're looking for situations where you have a gene on the Y

1447
01:22:07.518 --> 01:22:11.398
chromosome in blue, and then the same gene homologue might be on

1448
01:22:11.438 --> 01:22:15.238
the X chromosome, and that X chromosome gene is knocked out in this

1449
01:22:15.298 --> 01:22:19.118
experiment. What can we see in cells that have loss of Y

1450
01:22:19.158 --> 01:22:21.738
versus those cell lines that retain their Y chromosomes?

1451
01:22:22.238 --> 01:22:25.978
When we did this experiment, we found that actually in

1452
01:22:26.038 --> 01:22:29.998
loss of Y cell lines, there are two genes linked to the X chromosome

1453
01:22:30.038 --> 01:22:32.058
that are very, very strong dependencies.

1454
01:22:32.438 --> 01:22:35.178
So that means if you knock out the gene DDX3X

1455
01:22:35.758 --> 01:22:39.618
or EIF1AX, and the cells don't have a Y

1456
01:22:39.698 --> 01:22:43.498
chromosome to back up these genes, those cells die frequently.

1457
01:22:44.158 --> 01:22:48.138
So that gives us a first idea of what the things are that we could target

1458
01:22:48.878 --> 01:22:52.838
related to the X chromosome in loss of Y cells to potentially

1459
01:22:52.898 --> 01:22:55.438
attack cancer cells that have loss of Y.

1460
01:22:58.598 --> 01:22:59.118
All right.

1461
01:23:01.918 --> 01:23:03.538
And with this, I just want to summarize.

1462
01:23:03.678 --> 01:23:07.378
I've told you that somatic Y chromosome alterations are common across cancer

1463
01:23:07.398 --> 01:23:10.938
types. As I said, 30% to 40% across adult tumors, about

1464
01:23:11.098 --> 01:23:15.058
20% in pediatric tumors. Whole chromosome loss of Y compared to

1465
01:23:15.118 --> 01:23:17.058
other alterations is the most frequent

1466
01:23:18.558 --> 01:23:21.598
alteration of the Y chromosome, and its frequency varies a lot.

1467
01:23:22.338 --> 01:23:26.018
Loss of Y is associated with genomic instability, and particularly mutations or

1468
01:23:26.098 --> 01:23:30.018
loss of P53. It's associated with clinical features,

1469
01:23:30.038 --> 01:23:32.938
including outcome, at least in some tumor types.

1470
01:23:33.018 --> 01:23:36.688
However, we don't fully understand the exact driver mechanisms,

1471
01:23:36.798 --> 01:23:39.858
especially as they might vary between different tumor types.

1472
01:23:40.287 --> 01:23:44.217
And so I just want to go to a few open challenges that I encourage you to think

1473
01:23:44.298 --> 01:23:48.018
about or maybe talk to us and bring the field forward.

1474
01:23:48.578 --> 01:23:51.928
So the structure of the Y chromosome, as Lars has said, actually varies

1475
01:23:51.938 --> 01:23:55.778
substantially between individuals, ranging from 45 megabases to

1476
01:23:55.838 --> 01:23:59.598
over 80 megabases. But we're currently using only the reference

1477
01:23:59.718 --> 01:24:02.168
genome, which is about 62 megabases, right?

1478
01:24:02.578 --> 01:24:06.258
So what are we really missing there? What's variability between individuals?

1479
01:24:06.698 --> 01:24:10.518
Short-read sequencing cannot represent Y variation fully, and

1480
01:24:10.558 --> 01:24:14.198
that's just a limitation, that it doesn't account for all this length and

1481
01:24:14.858 --> 01:24:16.758
variability in the repeat frequencies.

1482
01:24:17.438 --> 01:24:20.398
One question I get frequently is, well, is Y simply

1483
01:24:20.438 --> 01:24:22.698
dispensable? The cells don't care.

1484
01:24:22.858 --> 01:24:25.958
I hope all three of us convinced you otherwise.

1485
01:24:26.438 --> 01:24:30.118
Is there a common phenotype of loss of Y in cancer, or does it

1486
01:24:30.178 --> 01:24:33.417
vary between tumor types? Again, something we don't fully understand yet.

1487
01:24:33.748 --> 01:24:37.718
And then how do mosaic loss of Y as it occurs in the blood and tumor loss

1488
01:24:37.758 --> 01:24:41.478
of Y relate? You already heard a little bit about this, but again, we're

1489
01:24:41.538 --> 01:24:45.358
still very early in understanding those interactions between the immune

1490
01:24:45.438 --> 01:24:49.298
system and the tumor. And with that, I'd like to thank you

1491
01:24:49.338 --> 01:24:53.008
for listening and coming. My lab, of course, Luis and

1492
01:24:53.038 --> 01:24:56.398
Teo, who are here and will present posters on this topic.

1493
01:24:56.798 --> 01:24:58.998
Meifang, I mentioned before, who wrote the algorithm.

